Introduction to Long-reads Bulk RNA-Seq data analysis

Cancer Genomics & Transcriptomics Course, EMBL-EBI

Alexey Larionov

27 June 2024

1. Introduction

This session is aimed at providing an initial practical experience with long-reads RNA-Seq data. Long-reads sequencing technology is changing at a very fast pace. So do the tools and algorithms for the data analysis. Many different tools exist for each task. Often the tools are technology-specific (i.e.Nanopore tools do not work for PacBio and vice versa).

Tools for this session were selected to illustrate the main steps required for QC, DGE (Differential Gene Expression) and DTU (Differential Transcript Usage) analyses, using Nanopore cDNA sequencing data as an example.

This document shows only selected elements of the code. The full code is provided in the accompanying scripts.

1.1 Source data: SG-NEx study

Data used in this session was generated by the SQ-NEx study. Briefly, the study extracted and sequenced RNA from several cancer cell lines to compare different RNA-seq options available in Nanopore: PCR-based cDNA, direct cDNA and direct-RNA sequencing. Samples selected for this session include PCR-based cDNA data from H9 and HEYA8 cell lines:

All selected samples were sequenced on the same day (2021-03-30) on the same Nanopore machine and flowcell (PromethION PRO002), for all samples the base calling was done by the same basecaller (guppy-3.2.10-GIS), and they had been prepared using the same library kit (SQK-PCB109). Please note that this data were created 3 years ago, so they may not represent the latest Nanopore sequencing and basecalling quality.

You may see more details about SQ-NEx study at

1.2 Conda environments

Historically, many tools used for long-read data analysis (Nanopore and PacBio alike) have been developed in Python. Conda is a package manager that is widely used in the Python community. In some sense, Conda is similar to apt in Linux or Homebrew in Mac: it is used to install software, and it can trace and install multiple dependencies when installing a tool. Unfortunately, some tools have conflicting dependencies, e.g.they may require different versions of the same library. Conda provides an easy solution for such conflicts: it allows loading different sets of dependencies (called environments) when running different tools. When a certain conda environment is needed, it can be easily activated without restarting the computer. When a different environment is needed, then the previous one can be de-activated, and the new one can be activated instead.

Check which conda environments are installed on your Virtual Machine:

conda env list

Amongst others, you should see nanopack, chopper and pychopper environments: they had been pre-installed for you to use during this session. Note that these environments are present, but not yet activated.

Check whether NanoPlot tool is available without activating the required conda environment:

which NanoPlot

Now activate the required environment and check whether NanoPlot tool becomes available:

conda activate nanopack
which NanoPlot
conda deactivate

Note that the name of the active conda environment is shown in front of the prompt. The required conda environments will be activated within the provided scripts, so you dont need to activate the environments manually for running scripts during this practical session.

Like during the short-reads practical session, many tools used in this long-reads session allow for multiprocessing. In most cases the scripts are written to request 14 threads because your Virtual Machine provides 16 cores (a couple of cores is left in case you browse the internet along with running scripts :)

Explore the ~/bulk-rnaseq/long_reads folder in your home directory. It should contain sub-folders for scripts, data and results. Again, there is no results within the folder yet. However, it is expected that you may make some during this session.

A separate folder is created for wf-transcriptomes pipeline. For now, it only contains the source data. Results will be added to this folder after the wf-transcriptomes run.

Again, there is a copy of the ~/bulk-rnaseq/long_reads folder on the Penelope Drive. It contains copies of the source data, scripts and expected results. You may copy files from Penelope Drive to your home folder, if needed. However, dont run, change or remove files directly on Penelope Drive.

3. Evaluate ONT data with NanoPack

NanoPack is a set of tools for quality control (QC) and filtering of Nanopore fastq files; it includes:

  • NanoPlot : QC for a single fastq file
  • NanoComp : comparison of quality metrics between fastq files
  • chopper : filtering of Nanopore fastq by quality metrics
  • and some other tools : https://github.com/wdecoster/nanopack

The NanoPlot and NanoComp tools are used by the scripts provided in /bulk-rnaseq/long_reads/scripts/s01_nanopack_qc folder.

Explore and run these scripts. Then review the selected output files mentioned below.

3.1 QC single fastq file with NanoPlot

NanoPlot can be started by the following code:

NanoPlot \
  --fastq "${input_fq_gz}" \
  --threads 14 \
  --drop_outliers \
  --outdir "${output_folder}"

See more details in the provided script. The script should run for 3-5 min. The full list of NanoPlot options is described at its GitHub page: https://github.com/wdecoster/NanoPlot

The output folder will contain many figures and a summary file NanoPlot-report.html. Open the summary file and find the plot showing Read length vs Average read quality using kernel density. It may look like this:

Does this figure show raw data or data already filtered by read quality? Was it a good or a bad quality sample?

3.2 Compare multiple fastq files with NanoComp

Comparison of the multiple fastqc files could be done by NanoComp (again, see details in the script):

NanoComp \
--fastq "${HEYA8_14}" "${HEYA8_24}" "${HEYA8_33}" "${H9_24}" "${H9_34}" "${H9_44}" \
--names HEYA8_14 HEYA8_24 HEYA8_33 H9_24 H9_34 H9_44 \
--threads 14 \
--outdir "${output_folder}"

The full list of NanoComp options is available at its GitHub page: https://github.com/wdecoster/nanocomp

The script should complete within 7-10 min. The output folder will contain many figures and a summary file NanoComp-report.html. Open the summary file and find the plot comparing average base call quality scores:

The figure above shows results for some samples for A539 and HepG2 cells from SG-NEX study. Of course, your results should look slightly different. Was there any read with average base quality at least 20? Make a rough estimate for the proportion of reads that would be retained after filtering by average base quality 7.

Find in the summary file the plot showing number of reads per sample. What was the largest number of reads amongst the studied samples? The files had been thinned to 10% of their original size. So, the original reads number was much larger.

4. Pre-processing of cDNA Nanopore data

After QC, we may need to filter and trim the data to remove failed reads. A generic filtering usually include removing reads with short length and low average quality. In our practical we will use Nanopacks tool called chopper for this.

The cDNA data should be additionally pre-processed to make sure that we only retain full length reads (containing both SSP and VNP primers), and orient the reads in a way that they represent the coding strand (again, based on the sequences of SSP and VNP primers - see the lecture). Then the primers should be chopped away. The Oxford Nanopore tool that does it is called Pychopper.

What a confusing naming! Remember: the Nanopacks chopper and the Nanopores Pychopper are different tools!

Scripts for this part of the parctical session are located in the /bulk-rnsseq/long-reads/scripts/s02_nanopore_preprocessing

4.1 Filter fastq file with chopper

Removing reads with average base quality below 7 and the length <500 is a common practice in analysis of Nanopore data (see s01_nanopore_filtering.sh script):

gunzip -c "${input_fq_gz}" | chopper -q 10 -l 500 | gzip > "${output_fq_gz}"

Note that at present (in Jun 2024) chopper does not recognize gzipped files. So it has to be wrapped in gunzip/gzip to process such files.

The full list of filters and options for chopper is available at its GitHub page:

  • https://github.com/wdecoster/chopper

The script should complete within 3-5 min. It will produce a fastq file containing only reads that passed the filter(s).

Just recently, Nanopack suggested using its NanoFilt tool, which has a similar functionality with the chopper. However, now NanoFilt is considered as an older and slower tool. Its quite a common case when bioinformatics tools deprecate within a very short time!

4.2 Trim and orient cDNA reads with Pychopper

Pychopper is a tool to identify, orient and trim full-length Nanopore cDNA reads:

  • https://github.com/epi2me-labs/pychopper

It detects SSP (Strand Switching Primer) and VNP (the anchored oligo-dT VN Primer) in the reads. Reads that contain both primers in a correct orientation are considered full-reads. The primer sequences can be used to derive the orientation of full-reads: e.g.SSP should be at the 5 end and reverse-complement of VNP at the 3 end of the coding strand. Because of the high error rate in the raw Nanopore data (especially in the data generated some years ago) Pychopper has to employ complex approximation algorithms to detect the primer sequences. In addition, Pychopper accounts for the distance between the putative primers.

Importantly, for Pychopper to work the primer trimming should be switched OFF during the basecalling (i.e.when fastq files are generated from the raw fast5 files).

The output of Pychopper includes

  • fastq with trimmed and properly oriented full-length reads
  • fastq-s with failed and rescued reads
  • tsv and pdf files with read counts and plots

This command is used for running Pychopper in our session (see the script for details):

pychopper \
-t 16 \
-m edlib \
-S "${statistics_tsv}" \
-r "${report_pdf}" \
-u "${unclassified_fq}" \
-w "${rescued_fq}" \
"${input_fq}" \
"${full_length_fq}"

These are examples of the plots from the Pychoppers summary pdf file :

The figure above shows examples of a good (on the left) and a bad (on the right) samples. Is the sample given to you for this practical session good or bad?

A low proportion of full reads might be rescued by increasing the sensitivity of the algorithm that identifies primers (parameter -q in the above command, see details in the Pychopper GitHub page). However, this may reduce the specificity of primer detection. In the recent versions of Pychopper the -q parameter is selected usisng a small sub-set of reads, before processing the entire file.

5. Nanopore wf-transcriptomes pipeline

5.1 Pipelines / Workflows

Till now we considered analyses one step at a time e.g.: QC, then filtering, then trimming etc. We have not discussed yet what is required to make a pipeline out of these steps:

  • Design the conceptual workflow that puts the right tools in the right order.
  • Install and configure all dependencies (i.e.the tools and resources required for analysis).
  • Align outputs of the upstream tools with input requirements of the downstream tools.
  • Arrange the locations of the source data, interim files and results.
  • Write scripts that assemble all the pieces together, log and paralellize the computation, etc.

In addition to understanding the bioinformatics tasks and tools, making a pipeline may require advanced IT and programming skills. In an attempt to take this burden out of the bio-medical researchers (and to avoid many amateurish mistakes), both Nanopore and PacBio made an effort to provide entire functional pipelines, in addition to the separate tools and conceptual guidance. Making pipelines is becoming more and more popular in the bioinformatics community.

5.2 Workflow Management Systems

Several workflow management systems have been developed for building bioinformatics pipelines such as Snakemake (https://snakemake.readthedocs.io/en/stable), Cromwell (https://cromwell.readthedocs.io/en/stable) or Nextflow (https://www.nextflow.io/). Some years ago it looked like Nanopore preferred Snakemake and PacBio preferred Cromwell for their pipelines. However, recently it seems that Nextflow is gaining popularity, not least because of the NF-Core: a large repository of Nextflow bioinformatics pipelines (https://nf-co.re/pipelines/).

In this practical you will try a Nextflow pipeline, which was developed by Oxford Nanopore for quantitative RNAseq analysis:

  • https://github.com/epi2me-labs/wf-transcriptomes

5.3 wf-transcriptomes pipeline overview

The first (now deprecated) Nanopores pipeline for quantitative RNAseq analysis was based on the paper of Love et al 2018 ( https://f1000research.com/articles/7-952/v3 ). It included alignment with minimap2 against a reference transcriptome, followed by counts with Salmon, differential genes expression (DGE) with edgeR and differential transcripts usage (DTU) analysis using R packages DEXSeq/stageR. That pipeline used Snakemake. Recently it has been substituted by the wf-transcriptomes, which uses Nextflow and has some additional steps (such as fusion detection with Jaffa, and transcriptome assembly).

Currently the wf-transcriptomes pipeline includes the following functionality:

  • Identifying RNA transcripts (using either cDNA or direct RNA reads)
  • Making reference aided transcriptome assembly
  • Annotating the assembled transcripts
  • Detecting gene fusions
  • Differential gene expression (DGE) analysis
  • Differential transcript usage (DTU) analysis

The differential expression steps could be done either using a pre-computed or assembled reference transcriptome.

Conceptually, the DGE part of this workflow is similar to the short-reads DGE analysis that we discussed this morning. The main differences from the short-reads analysis that we used in the morning include:

  • minimap2 for mapping (instead of performing quasi-mapping by Salmon itself).
  • edgeR instead of DESeq2 package for actual differential expression analysis.

5.4 Running wf-transcriptomes pipeline

The instructions below will guide you through the main steps needed to run the pipeline during this practical session. Many more technical details are available in the pipelines GitHub repository (https://github.com/epi2me-labs/wf-transcriptomes).

Go to /bulk-rnaseq/long_reads/wf-transcriptomes/source-data folder:

The folder with fastq files

In this case, the files are organised into sub-folders according to their barcodes, provided in the sample sheet above. The fastq files were sliced, containing only Chr20. This allows running this test dataset within ~15 min.

The resources

In this case you can see the refernce genome (hg38 chromosome 20), the genome annotations (the gencode 22 gtf file) and chr20 folder with resources required for the fusion detection.

5.4.2 Run the pipeline

Go to /bulk-rnaseq/long_reads/scripts/s03_wf-transcriptomes folder. Review and run the script:

./run_wf_transcriptomes.sh &> run_wf_transcriptomes.log # Start the pipeline recording output to the log

The actual part of the script that launches the pipeline is:

cd "${working_folder}"

nextflow run epi2me-labs/wf-transcriptomes \
--fastq  source_data/fastq \
--de_analysis \
--ref_genome source_data/hg38_chr20.fa \
--transcriptome-source reference-guided \
--ref_annotation source_data/gencode.v22.annotation.chr20.gtf \
--direct_rna \
--minimap2_index_opts '-k 15' \
--sample_sheet source_data/sample_sheet.csv \
--jaffal_refBase source_data/chr20/ \
--jaffal_genome hg38_chr20 \
--jaffal_annotation genCode22 \
-profile standard

The meaning of this pipeline-launching command is the following:

  • it instructs nextflow to start the epi2me-labs/wf-transcriptomes workflow
  • provides the location of the folder with source fastq files
  • instructs to perform differential expression analysis (de_analysis)
  • provides the location of the reference genome
  • instructs to assemble the reference-guided transcriptome
  • provides the location of the genome annotation file
  • informs about the type pf analysed RNAseq data (direct_rna)
  • sets some specific parameter for minimap2
  • provides location of the sample sheet
  • provides some instructions for the fusion detection with Jaffal
  • profile standard instructs the workflow to use Docker (instead of Singularity)

Many more settings, which could be used with this workflow, are described in the workflows GitHub page.

5.4.3 Review the results

During the run the workflow reports progress to the log (or to the terminal, if you dont record the output to the log). The entire workflow should complete within ~10-12 min. After the completion of the workflow go to the /long_reads/wf-transcriptomes folder.

Several sub-folders and files will be created in the folder where the pipeline had been started (in /long_reads/wf-transcriptomes/ in our case). Some folders are created by the Nextflow: the work folder (and maybe some hidden files and folders). These folders contain some technical information that may b helpful for the debugging, if something went wrong.

The actual output of the workflow should be available in the folder called outout:

6. Conclusion

This practical session was intended to give you an first-hand experience with long-reads RNA-seq data analysis.

  • First, you tried some generic steps for Nanopore QC and pre-processing (NanoPlot, NanoComp, chopper).
  • Then you did a cDNA-specific step: selecting and orienting full-length RNAseq reads (Pychopper).
  • Finally, you got an experience with running an entire multi-step workflow, provided by Nanopore for RNA-Seq DGE / DTU analyses.

The workflow illustrated

  • conceptual continuity of DGE methods between short-reads and long-reads analyses (minimap2, Salmon, edgeR) and
  • new opportunities provided by the Long-reads that allow studying Differential Transcript Usage (DTU: DEXSeq, stageR )
